WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.200
Speaker 1: Welcome back to the show, today we are talking about shipping small reliable systems.

00:00:05.400 --> 00:00:09.200
Speaker 2: Thanks for having me, it is great to be here again.

00:00:09.400 --> 00:00:14.800
Speaker 1: So, let's start with the basics, what does a minimum viable pipeline actually look like?

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:20.600
Speaker 2: In my experience it is three things, intake, processing, and a human approval gate.

00:00:20.800 --> 00:00:25.200
Speaker 1: Right, and, the approval gate is the part most teams skip first.

00:00:25.400 --> 00:00:29.600
Speaker 2: Which is exactly backwards, because trust is the whole product.

00:00:29.800 --> 00:00:33.800
Speaker 1: Can you give a concrete example from a project you shipped?

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:39.400
Speaker 2: Sure, we built a transcript workflow where every export required an approved version.

00:00:39.600 --> 00:00:44.200
Speaker 1: That sounds slow though, did reviewers push back on the extra step?

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:49.600
Speaker 2: At first yes, but the audit trail saved us in the first compliance review.

00:00:49.800 --> 00:00:54.000
Speaker 1: That matches what we hear from other teams about governance.

00:00:54.200 --> 00:00:59.200
Speaker 2: The other lesson is to keep raw output immutable, never edit the source of truth.

00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:03.600
Speaker 1: How do you handle sections where the audio quality drops?

00:01:03.800 --> 00:01:08.600
Speaker 2: We flag low confidence segments and route reviewer attention there first.

00:01:08.800 --> 00:01:13.000
Speaker 1: So the machine does the pass and the human does the judgment.

00:01:13.200 --> 00:01:18.200
Speaker 2: Exactly, and, that division of labor is what makes the effort reduction real.

00:01:18.400 --> 00:01:22.800
Speaker 1: What about summaries, do you generate those automatically too?

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:27.600
Speaker 2: Yes, but grounded only in transcript content, no invented claims allowed.

00:01:27.800 --> 00:01:31.800
Speaker 1: That seems like the right guardrail for derived content.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.400
Speaker 2: It is, and every summary records which transcript version it came from.

00:01:36.600 --> 00:01:41.600
Speaker 1: Before we wrap up, what is the one thing listeners should do tomorrow?

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:47.000
Speaker 2: Write down your approval boundary, decide what a human must sign off on.

00:01:47.200 --> 00:01:51.600
Speaker 1: That is a great note to end on, thanks so much for joining us.

00:01:51.800 --> 00:01:54.400
Speaker 2: Thank you, this was fun.

